    <title>Teenage Engineering’s new OP–XY makes me wish I had a bigger budget for music gear</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="The Teenage Engineering OP-XY against a white background." src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/ryr3Xx3C8BLmPds5t7-hFORYVyo=/0x0:3588x2392/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73723954/teenageengineering1.0.jpg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;&lt;em&gt;The Teenage Engineering OP-XY feels like an upgraded version of the company’s six-year-old OP-Z.&lt;/em&gt; | Image: Teenage Engineering&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="RSMnyr"&gt;Teenage Engineering’s new &lt;a href="https://teenage.engineering/products/op-xy"&gt;OP-XY&lt;/a&gt; is a portable synthesizer and sequencer that looks similar to the company’s &lt;a href="https://teenage.engineering/store/op-1-field/?srsltid=AfmBOooacg__9SKptrN6z36SqsSz2iNnGPNsQvYrQey68CAe6jb1ASaq"&gt;OP–1 Field&lt;/a&gt;. But functionally it’s instead a more capable upgrade to the company’s &lt;a href="https://teenage.engineering/products/op-z"&gt;six-year-old OP-Z&lt;/a&gt;, with a stronger focus on layering sounds with various effects and a steeper $2,299 price tag.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="I4ZsJZ"&gt;With an “anodized, all-black finish,” the OP-XY is yet another delightful example of Teenage Engineering’s design chops. Its black and white motif accented with a grayscale gradient running across its 16 sequencer inputs is the antithesis of the &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/24191461/playdate-ereader-app-playbook-panic-teenage-engineering"&gt;bright yellow Playdate handheld&lt;/a&gt; that Teenage Engineering helped Panic design. Unlike the $429 OP-Z that relied on a mobile device like a smartphone for its screen, the OP-XY now has a black and...&lt;/p&gt;
